{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"246c2172-cc7b-43bb-b835-20ec813ab100","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK needed. Inside the container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- For **ARM64** containers, use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64`.\n- To get the file out, use `docker cp <container>:/tmp/trace.nettrace .`\n- Open the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) for analysis.\n- If you hit this often, consider adding the curl/chmod lines to your `Dockerfile` so the tool is always available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94408298-82e1-406d-83b6-47ca0c4c59d0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. You can download the single-file version from the .NET diagnostics releases.\n3. For Linux containers, you'd use `curl` to download the tool directly.\n\n\n4. I'll walk through the practical steps to get this working.","outputTokens":438,"requestId":"9818:2D1D23:AF96D3:CDC0BD:69F40241"},"id":"be5ef826-c3ea-4d2b-b086-515c11f84b5f","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:51.851Z","parentId":"7ada4aa2-c114-4474-9191-da46999a3d73"}
